  "text": "Mixed prostatic carcinomas are rare; they demonstrate a combination of malignant epithelial or sarcomatoid components [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The epithelial variant of these carcinomas is often a high-grade acine adenocarcinoma mixed with squamous, urothelial, neuroendocrine, ductal, mucinous (colloid), signet ring, oncocytic, basal cell, and lymphoepithelioma-like components [CITATION_3] . The origin and utility of identification of these mixed carcinomas has been highly controversial; they have been thought by some authors to be derived from a single cell of origin, and are the product of one or multiple types of differentiation or",
